 Yes, the code is vulnerable to a Denial of Service (DoS) attack. The function `sparse_dump_region` reads data from a file until the end of the sparse map, without checking if the file size has changed during the operation. If an attacker modifies the file being archived after the sparse map has been created but before the file is fully read, they can cause an infinite read loop, leading to a DoS vulnerability. This is the same issue described in CVE-2018-20482 and CWE-835.

The vulnerability is in the following part of the code:

```c++
while (bytes_left > 0)
{
  size_t bufsize = (bytes_left > BLOCKSIZE)? BLOCKSIZE : bytes_left;
  size_t bytes_read;

  blk = find_next_block();
  bytes_read = safe_read(file->fd, blk->buffer, bufsize);
  //...
}
```

The code should check if the file size has changed and update the `bytes_left` variable accordingly.

